t of the poet-monk as a distinct actor in the Chinese literary world, arguing for the importance of religious practice in medieval literature. As they witnessed the collapse of the world around them, these monks wove together the frayed threads of their traditions to establish an elite-style Chinese Buddhist poetry. Poet-Monks shows that during the transformative period of the Tang-Song transition, Buddhist monks were at the forefront of poetic innovation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBuddhist monkszChinaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aBuddhist poetry, ChinesezChinaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPoetryxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aPoets, ChineseyTang dynasty, 618-907. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aChinese Buddhist, poetry, East Asian religious studies, Buddhism, Tang poetry, meditation, literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150177385340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773853423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773853/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles